  "prompt": "What is plate tectonics?",
  "response": "Plate tectonics is a scientific theory that explains how the Earth's outer layer, called the lithosphere, is divided into large, rigid plates that move and interact with each other. Key points include:\n\n1. Structure:\n- The Earth's lithosphere is broken into about 7-8 major plates and several smaller plates\n- These plates float on the semi-fluid asthenosphere beneath them\n\n2. Movement:\n- Plates move very slowly, typically a few centimeters per year\n- They can move apart, collide, or slide past each other\n\n3. Plate boundaries:\n- Divergent boundaries: Plates move apart, creating new crust (e.g., mid-ocean ridges)\n- Convergent boundaries: Plates collide, with one often sliding under another (subduction)\n- Transform boundaries: Plates slide horizontally past each other\n\n4. Geological effects:\n- Causes earthquakes\n- Forms mountain ranges\n- Creates volcanic activity\n- Drives continental drift\n\n5. Historical significance:\n- Explains how continents were once connected in a supercontinent called Pangaea\n- Helps understand Earth's geological processes and evolution\n\nPlate tectonics is crucial in understanding the Earth's geological structure and dynamic surface processes.",
